#state benchmark for DRG
#to find a benchmark for providers in different states using DRG realated data in different states, including total discharges, covered charges, total payments and medicare payments.
DRG_State_avg <- inpatientCharges %>% group_by(DRG.Definition, Provider.State) %>%
       summarise( mean_total_discharges          = mean(Total.Discharges),
                  mean_average_covered_charges   = mean(Average.Covered.Charges),
                  mean_average_total_payments    = mean(Average.Total.Payments),
                  mean_average_medicare_payments = mean(Average.Medicare.Payments),                 
                  mean_count_trans =n())
head(DRG_State_avg)
## # A tibble: 6 x 7
## # Groups:   DRG.Definition [1]
##   DRG.Definition Provider.State mean_total_disc… mean_average_co…
##   <chr>          <chr>                     <dbl>            <dbl>
## 1 039 - EXTRACR… AK                         23             34805.
## 2 039 - EXTRACR… AL                         38.2           32044.
## 3 039 - EXTRACR… AR                         40.8           27463.

#calculate the ratio of each provider's charge to the benchmark in the state
#to see how many times that a provider's total discharge/covered charge/total payment/medicare payment of DRG surpass the benchmark for the DRG in that state

per_provider <- inpatientCharges %>% 
       left_join(DRG_State_avg, by=c("DRG.Definition","Provider.State")) %>%
       mutate( 
            ratio_total_discharges_st = Total.Discharges/mean_total_discharges,
            ratio_average_covered_charges_st = Average.Covered.Charges/mean_average_covered_charges,
            ratio_average_total_payments_st = Average.Total.Payments/mean_average_total_payments,
            ratio_average_medicare_payments_st = Average.Medicare.Payments/mean_average_medicare_payments) %>%
       select(-mean_total_discharges,
              -mean_average_covered_charges,
              -mean_average_total_payments,
              -mean_average_medicare_payments,
              -mean_count_trans,
              -Total.Discharges,
              -Average.Covered.Charges,
              -Average.Total.Payments,
              -Average.Medicare.Payments
           ) %>% arrange(Provider.Id, DRG.Definition) 
#national benchmark for DRG
#compare each provider's charge for DRG to the benchmark in national wide
#to see how many times that a provider's total discharge/covered charge/total payment/medicare payment of DRG surpass the benchmark for the DRG in national wide

DRG_National_avg <-inpatientCharges %>% group_by(DRG.Definition) %>%
  summarise(mean_national_avg_total_discharges = mean(Total.Discharges),
            mean_national_avg_covered_charges = mean(Average.Covered.Charges),
            mean_national_avg_total_payments = mean(Average.Total.Payments),
            mean_national_avg_medicare_payments = mean(Average.Medicare.Payments),
            mean_count_trans =n())

DRG_provider <- inpatientCharges %>% 
       left_join(DRG_National_avg, by=c("DRG.Definition")) %>%
       mutate( 
            ratio_total_discharges_national = Total.Discharges/mean_national_avg_total_discharges,
            ratio_average_covered_charges_national = Average.Covered.Charges/mean_national_avg_covered_charges,
            ratio_average_total_payments_national = Average.Total.Payments/mean_national_avg_total_payments,
            ratio_average_medicare_payments_national = Average.Medicare.Payments/mean_national_avg_medicare_payments) %>%
       select(-mean_national_avg_total_discharges,
              -mean_national_avg_covered_charges,
              -mean_national_avg_total_payments,
              -mean_national_avg_medicare_payments,
              -mean_count_trans,
              -Total.Discharges,
              -Average.Covered.Charges,
              -Average.Total.Payments,
              -Average.Medicare.Payments
           ) %>% arrange(DRG.Definition) 
#find top 5 costly DRG in each state based on the average total payments 

top_mean_avgtpy_st = inpatientCharges %>% group_by(Provider.State, DRG.Definition) %>%
  summarise(mean_average_total_payment = mean(Average.Total.Payments)) %>% 
  top_n(5,mean_average_total_payment)
# calculate a benchmark of the average number of time that the top 5 costly DRG has been filled in each state
# to see how many times a healthcare provider fill the top 5 costly DRG greater than the benchmark 
# if a provider has an abnormal large number than other providers in the same state, it could be suspicious
#the reason for me to add the feature:pricey_DRG_ratio is because I assume that healthcare providers with fraud would like to fill more costly DRG because of the high amount of money they could get paid

df <-data.frame("Provider.Id" = unique(inpatientCharges$Provider.Id), "pricey_DRG_ratio" = 0 )

ct=1

for (st in unique(top_mean_avgtpy_st$Provider.State)) {
  drg_list_state=top_mean_avgtpy_st$DRG.Definition[top_mean_avgtpy_st$Provider.State==st]
  for (pro_id in unique(inpatientCharges$Provider.Id[inpatientCharges$Provider.State==st])) {top5_total_discharges=sum(inpatientCharges$Total.Discharges[inpatientCharges$Provider.State==st & inpatientCharges$Provider.Id == pro_id & (inpatientCharges$DRG.Definition==drg_list_state[1]|
inpatientCharges$DRG.Definition==drg_list_state[2]|                                                             inpatientCharges$DRG.Definition==drg_list_state[3]|
  inpatientCharges$DRG.Definition==drg_list_state[4]|                                                           inpatientCharges$DRG.Definition==drg_list_state[5])])
      
  df$pricey_DRG_ratio[df$Provider.Id==pro_id] =top5_total_discharges/mean(inpatientCharges$Total.Discharges[inpatientCharges$Provider.State==st & (inpatientCharges$DRG.Definition==drg_list_state[1]|
inpatientCharges$DRG.Definition==drg_list_state[2]|                                                             inpatientCharges$DRG.Definition==drg_list_state[3]|
  inpatientCharges$DRG.Definition==drg_list_state[4]|                                                           inpatientCharges$DRG.Definition==drg_list_state[5])])
  ct=ct+1
      }
}
df_w_ratio= inpatientCharges %>% 
  full_join(df, by ="Provider.Id")
## Warning: Column `Provider.Id` joining character vector and factor, coercing
## into character vector
# find top 5 commonly happened DRG in each state
# calculate a benchmark of the average number of time that the top 5 commonly happened DRG has been filled in each state
# to see how many times a healthcare provider fill the top 5 commonly happened DRG greater than the benchmark 
# if a provider has an abnormal large number than other providers in the same state, it could be suspicious
#the reason for me to add the feature:common_DRG_ratio is because I assume that healthcare providers with fraud would like to fill more common DRG because they want to hide their fraudulent actions. 

top_DRG_st = inpatientCharges %>% group_by(Provider.State, DRG.Definition) %>%
  summarise(mean_total_discharges = mean(Total.Discharges)) %>% 
  top_n(5,mean_total_discharges)


df1 <-data.frame("Provider.Id" = unique(inpatientCharges$Provider.Id), "common_DRG_ratio" = 0 )

n=1

for (st in unique(top_DRG_st$Provider.State)) {
  drg_list_state=top_DRG_st$DRG.Definition[top_DRG_st$Provider.State==st]
  for (pro_id in unique(inpatientCharges$Provider.Id[inpatientCharges$Provider.State==st])) {top5_total_discharges=sum(inpatientCharges$Total.Discharges[inpatientCharges$Provider.State==st & inpatientCharges$Provider.Id == pro_id & (inpatientCharges$DRG.Definition==drg_list_state[1]|
inpatientCharges$DRG.Definition==drg_list_state[2]|                                                             inpatientCharges$DRG.Definition==drg_list_state[3]|
  inpatientCharges$DRG.Definition==drg_list_state[4]|                                                           inpatientCharges$DRG.Definition==drg_list_state[5])])
      
  df1$common_DRG_ratio[df1$Provider.Id==pro_id] =top5_total_discharges/mean(inpatientCharges$Total.Discharges[inpatientCharges$Provider.State==st & (inpatientCharges$DRG.Definition==drg_list_state[1]|
inpatientCharges$DRG.Definition==drg_list_state[2]|                                                             inpatientCharges$DRG.Definition==drg_list_state[3]|
  inpatientCharges$DRG.Definition==drg_list_state[4]|                                                           inpatientCharges$DRG.Definition==drg_list_state[5])])
  n=n+1
      }
}

df1_w_ratio= inpatientCharges %>% 
  full_join(df1, by ="Provider.Id")
## Warning: Column `Provider.Id` joining character vector and factor, coercing
## into character vector
#join all the features together and form a new dataframe
#10 new features are pricey_DRG_ratio,common_DRG_ratio,ratio_total_discharges_national,ratio_average_covered_charges_national,ratio_average_total_payments_national,ratio_average_medicare_payments_national,ratio_total_discharges_st,ratio_average_covered_charges_st,ratio_average_total_payments_st,and ratio_average_medicare_payments_st.

provider_ratio_df = per_provider %>% left_join(df_w_ratio[,c("Provider.Id","DRG.Definition","pricey_DRG_ratio")], by =c("Provider.Id","DRG.Definition"))

provider_ratio_df = provider_ratio_df %>% left_join(df1_w_ratio[,c("Provider.Id","DRG.Definition","common_DRG_ratio")], by =c("Provider.Id","DRG.Definition"))


provider_ratio_df = provider_ratio_df %>% left_join(DRG_provider[,c("Provider.Id","DRG.Definition",                                                             "ratio_total_discharges_national","ratio_average_covered_charges_national","ratio_average_total_payments_national","ratio_average_medicare_payments_national")], by =c("Provider.Id","DRG.Definition"))

preparing data for clustering

subset the numeric data and standardize the data

data_cluster = provider_ratio_df[,9:18]
#head(data_cluster)
sum(is.na(data_cluster))
## [1] 0
data_cluster = scale(data_cluster)
use kmean for clustering
conbine the use of total within sum of squares and the ratio of between cluster sum of squares and total sum of squares to find the ideal number of clusters
#km = kmeans(x = data_cluster,centers = 5,iter.max=1000,nstart=25)
            #, algorithm = "MacQueen")
#if (km$ifault==4) { kms = kmeans(X, kms$centers, algorithm="MacQueen"); }

within_ss = sapply(1:15,FUN = function(x) kmeans(x = data_cluster,centers = x,iter.max = 1000,nstart = 25,algorithm = "MacQueen")$tot.withinss)
ggplot(data=data.frame(cluster = 1:15,within_ss),aes(x=cluster,y=within_ss))+
  geom_line(col='steelblue',size=1.2)+
  geom_point()+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(1,15,1))

ratio_ss = sapply(1:15,FUN = function(x) {km = kmeans(x = data_cluster,centers = x,iter.max = 1000,nstart = 25,algorithm = "MacQueen")
km$betweenss/km$totss} )
ggplot(data=data.frame(cluster = 1:15,ratio_ss),aes(x=cluster,y=ratio_ss))+
  geom_line(col='steelblue',size=1.2)+
  geom_point()+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(1,15,1))

Conclusion

Based on the analysis above, I would say healthcare providers in cluster 1 are highly suspicious. Reasons are listed as follows: 1). looking into the details of each cluster in km$center, I could compare each cluster’s differnece in the selected variables. And I found that custer 1 usually has a higher number in almost all variables compared to the other clusters. Specifically, cluster1 has a extremly high value in ratio_total_discharges_st,pricey_DRG_ratio, common_DRG_ratio, ratio_total_discharges_national. For example, the ratio_total_discharges_st of cluster 1 is about 3.75 while the other clusters usully have a number around 0.5 (here we measure in absolute values since the number represents the distance of a point away from the culster’s center). 2) the pricey_DRG_ratio and common_DRG_ratio in cluster1 is almost 4 times higher than other culsters, which could mean some healthcare providers in cluster1 has abnormal high amount of pricey clinical conditions diagnoses and common clinical conditions diagnoses than other providers in the same state. Some fraud might exist and need further investigation. 3) The visulization of the clusters could somewhat prove my viewpoints; a few points in cluster 1 are far away from the center. Also, from the graph, I would say some suspicious providers also exist in cluster 5 becuse of the distribution.
